Date: Wed, 6 May 1998 14:25:14 +0100 (BST)
From: D Stevenson <ds@holyrood.ed.ac.uk>

I recall hearing about Arctic explorers getting ill from toxic doses of
vitamin A both from polar bear liver and from sledge-dog liver (Vit-A
concentrated from the fish they were fed on). Is it OK to eat the rest of the
dog or bear, but for risk of Trichinella (which cooking would kill if fuel
available)?
Only horse-derived cases of trichinosis which I have heard of were in
France! The Australian complaint seems well grounded.
--
David Stevenson,
Public Health Sciences,
University of Edinburgh,
Scotland.
e-mail: ds@holyrood.ed.ac.uk
