Date: Wed, 06 May 1998 13:58:17 -0400
From: Robert A. LaBudde <ral@lcfltd.com>

It should be noted that Trichina can be killed either by heating at 144 F
(62 C) instant, or by holding meat frozen for a period of time. For example,
the USDA regulations (9 CFR 318.10) state:
(2) Refrigerating. At any stage of preparation and after preparatory
chilling to a temperature of not above 40 F. or preparatory freezing, all
parts of the muscle tissue of pork or product containing such tissue shall
be subjected continuously to a temperature not higher than one of those
specified in table 1, the duration of such refrigeration at the specified
temperature being dependent on the thickness of the meat or inside
dimensions of the container.
TABLE 1: REQUIRED PERIOD OF FREEZING AT TEMPERATURE INDICATED
Temperature F. Group 1 (Days) Group 2 (Days)
5 20 30
-10 10 20
-20 6 12

Notes: Group 1 = pieces < 6" in size, Group 2 = pieces > 6" in size
It may be that northern peoples, such as Eskimos (Inuit), may solve their
winter cooking problems with Trichina by leaving the meat to remain frozen
for a week or two at artic temperatures before consumption.
--
Robert A. LaBudde, PhD, PAS, Dpl. ACAFS e-mail: ral@lcfltd.com
Least Cost Formulations, Ltd. URL: http://lcfltd.com/
824 Timberlake Drive Tel: 757-467-0954
Virginia Beach, VA 23464-3239 Fax: 757-467-2947
[Storing food in pits dug into the frozen tundra is a traditional technique
of the Inuit, whether in North America or northern Russia. - Mod.MHJ
